<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">40195947</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>29</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1364-548X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>61</Volume><Issue>36</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Apr</Month><Day>29</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Chemical communications (Cambridge, England)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Chem Commun (Camb)</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Anhydrous salts for non-corrosive aluminium battery electrolytes.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>6639</StartPage><EndPage>6642</EndPage><MedlinePgn>6639-6642</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1039/d5cc00981b</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Commercial aluminium triflate and aluminium bis(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide salts are hydrates, which renders water containing electrolytes that passivate electrodes through Al(OH)<sub>3</sub> formation. By acid-base reactions we produce anhydrous salts and the resulting anhydrous electrolytes demonstrate enhanced electrochemical activity, paving the way for aluminium battery development.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hosaka</LastName><ForeName>Tomooki</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-5922-8320</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Physics, Chalmers University of Technology, 41296 G&#xf6;teborg, Sweden. hosaka@rs.tus.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Johansson</LastName><ForeName>Patrik</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-9907-117X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Physics, Chalmers University of Technology, 41296 G&#xf6;teborg, Sweden. hosaka@rs.tus.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>ALISTORE-European Resear